CHAIN OF THOUGHT — FOLLOW EVERY STEP IN ORDER
----------------------------------------------------------------
Before producing any JSON output, think through each step 
silently and thoroughly. Do not skip steps.

STEP 1 — IDENTIFY CORE SERVICE PAGES
   From core_services:
   - Does each service deserve its own page?
   - Or are services closely related enough to share a page?
   - Rule: if a buyer would search specifically for that service 
     by name — it deserves its own page.
   - Rule: if a business has a parent service with sub-services 
     — create a parent page + child pages.

   CONSOLIDATION CHECK — RUN BEFORE ASSIGNING ANY SERVICE PAGES:
   For every pair of services ask three questions:
   Q1: Do they solve the same buyer problem?
   Q2: Would the same buyer type search for both?
   Q3: Would both pages have near-identical section structures?

   If yes to all three — consolidate into ONE page.
   Rules for consolidation:
   - Name the page after the broader buyer problem not a service name
   - List both services as sub-topics within that page
   - Set entity_represented to cover both services
   - Add this note to why_it_exists:
     "consolidated: [service A] and [service B] solve identical 
     buyer problem — separate pages would create thin content 
     and keyword cannabilisation"
   - Do NOT create individual pages for either service after 
     consolidating — they are covered within the consolidated page

   Example:
   "Drain cleaning" + "Blocked drain repair" + "Drain unblocking"
   consolidated into ONE page: "Drain Cleaning and Blockage Removal"
   NOT three separate service pages

STEP 2 — DECIDE LOCATION PAGE STRATEGY
   From service_reach + locations + business_type:
   
   Ask three questions:
   Q1: Does location matter to how this buyer searches?
       Local service businesses — YES
       National SaaS or agencies — NO
   
   Q2: Do services vary by location or are they identical?
       Identical services across cities — one page per city
       Different services per city — service x city pages
   
   Q3: How many location x service combinations exist?
       Few combinations (under 6) — flat city pages
       Many combinations (6 or more) — parent area page 
       + individual city pages under it
   
   Apply the right approach and record your reasoning 
   in location_page_strategy.

STEP 3 — IDENTIFY TRUST AND CONVERSION PAGES
   From trust_drivers + buying_cycle + sophistication_level:
   - Does buying cycle length justify a dedicated process page?
   - Does skepticism_level = high justify a case study page?
     → If yes — case_study_parent is must_have not should_have
   - Does skepticism_level = medium justify a case study page?
     → If yes — case_study_parent is should_have
   - Does buyer sophistication justify a pricing page?
   - Does business model justify a how it works page?
   
   Only recommend these if trust_drivers or buyer_types 
   directly support them.

   CONTENT TONE RULE FOR CTA LANGUAGE:
   - If content_tone = empathetic → about page and contact page
     CTA language must reflect buyer vulnerability.
     Use: Free Consultation, Book a Visit, Talk to Us
     Never use: Get a Quote, Submit a Request, Contact Us
     Flag this reasoning in why_it_exists for those pages.

STEP 4 — IDENTIFY INDUSTRY OR VERTICAL PAGES
   From business_type + buyer_types + core_services:
   - Does this business serve distinct industries or verticals?
   - Would a buyer in that vertical search for industry-specific 
     services?
   - Only recommend if buyer_types explicitly reference 
     different industries or verticals.

STEP 5 — ASSIGN PRIORITY TO EVERY PAGE
   For each page ask:
   - Can the business convert a buyer without this page? 
     → NO = must_have
   - Does this page significantly improve trust or conversion?
     → YES = should_have
   - Does this page add depth but is not critical for launch?
     → YES = nice_to_have

   AUTO-ESCALATION RULES — APPLY BEFORE FINAL PRIORITY ASSIGNMENT:
   - If skepticism_level = high → case_study_parent 
     automatically escalates to must_have regardless of other factors
   - If content_tone = empathetic → about page 
     automatically escalates to must_have regardless of other factors
     Reason: vulnerable buyers (health, legal, mental health) will 
     not convert without seeing the humans behind the business

STEP 6 — BUILD PAGE HIERARCHY
   - Assign parent_page for every child page
   - Top level pages have empty string as parent_page
   - Ensure hierarchy is logical — no orphan pages
   - Services page is parent of individual service pages
   - Locations page (if exists) is parent of city pages


PAGE TYPES REFERENCE
----------------------------------------------------------------
Use only these page_type values:

home              — single, always required
service_parent    — umbrella page for multiple services
service           — individual service page
service_location  — service specific to a city or region
location_area     — city or region landing page
location_parent   — parent page for all location pages
about             — trust, team, credentials, story
case_study        — proof of results, client stories
case_study_parent — parent page listing all case studies
pricing           — cost, packages, engagement models
contact           — conversion, quote request, call booking
process           — how the service works step by step
industry          — vertical specific service page
industry_parent   — parent page for all industry pages
faq               — buyer objections and questions answered
blog_home         — content hub landing page

BLOG HOME RULE:
Only recommend blog_home when ALL THREE conditions are true:
- buying_cycle is medium or long (weeks or months)
- business_model is retainer or recurring
- buyer requires education before converting
Never recommend for transactional or emergency service businesses.


